    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1160891696" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1160891696" />
    <a title="Romance Readers Retreat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27541024-romance-readers-retreat"><img alt="Romance Readers Retreat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468271387p2/27541024.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1160891696?book_show_action=true">Jan 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Romance Readers Retreat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Romance Readers Retreat" href="/user/show/27541024-romance-readers-retreat">Romance Readers Retreat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1160891696" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17556854438336932252">This is a good book. This is a really good book. In fact, this may be one of my all time favorite erotic romance novels, at least in my top 10. <br/><br/>Normally I am not one to express a lot of emotion when reading a book, but this book had me blubbering like a blithering idiot one minute, and then laughing out loud a little while later. Nikki can really write, and I don&apos;t say that kind of thing easily.<br/><br/>The story is rather simple, Grant Wilkerson is a damaged man, isolated by his scars, both visible and </span>
  <span id="freeText17556854438336932252" style="display:none">This is a good book. This is a really good book. In fact, this may be one of my all time favorite erotic romance novels, at least in my top 10. <br /><br />Normally I am not one to express a lot of emotion when reading a book, but this book had me blubbering like a blithering idiot one minute, and then laughing out loud a little while later. Nikki can really write, and I don't say that kind of thing easily.<br /><br />The story is rather simple, Grant Wilkerson is a damaged man, isolated by his scars, both visible and invisible. He works with an amazing counselor, Andre Chevalier, who manages to dig deep into Grant's soul and pull out the noble man beneath his monstrous appearance.<br /><br />Renata Koreman is a beautiful woman with a horrible past. She first came to Andre as a shy, mute and damaged young woman. But Andre, doing what he does best, is able to bring out the truly brave woman hidden inside her.<br /><br />When Grant and Renata finally get together, sparks fly immediately, but this is not your normal erotic romance filled with wall to wall sex. It takes it's time to build these characters. To explain how and why they are the way they are. Andre is almost too good to be true. I don't know if counselors like him really exist, but I sure hope so.<br /><br />The book is split into three parts, part one is The Monster, part two is The Mouse, and part three is The Monster and the Mouse. I can't imagine a better way to tell this remarkable story. <br /><br />The book is the first of a series. I'm not sure how many books there will be, nor when the next book is due out. But I want to assure you that, although this book does end with a few things unresolved, and a possible danger threatening their happiness, it does not end in a normal cliffhanger. If she never wrote another book in this series, this book would still feel complete.<br /><br />I can't stress this enough. You should pickup this book. I promise you won't regret it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17556854438336932252" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

